[normal]Resid[bold]ence test[bold]Overview 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]a)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]‘Lawful’
[normal] – determining
[normal] whether
[normal] a person is lawfully resident 
[normal]may 
[normal]in itself 
[normal]require access to the courts. Legal aid, however, would not be available to 
[normal]re
[normal]solve a dispute as to the lawfulness of residence.
[normal]b)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]‘Residence’
[normal] – 
[normal]British children resident abroad
[normal] could be precluded
[normal] from obtaining legal aid to bring a claim in th
[normal]e Family Court that they should be returned to the UK. It would also preclude persons wrongly removed from the UK
[normal] 
[normal]from being eligible for legal aid to pursue their claim
[normal] for damages and/or lawful return
[normal].
[normal]c)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]‘Continuously’
[normal] – 
[normal]a person who r
[normal]esided in the UK for 
[normal]six months and then
[normal] left the UK for periods amounting to more than 30 days could not rely on the previous period of six months to accumulate the qualifying 12 month period
[normal]. 
[normal]d)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]‘12 month period’
[normal] – 
[normal]a British citizen 
[normal]or E
[normal]uropean 
[normal]E
[normal]conomic 
[normal]A
[normal]rea (EEA)
[normal] national 
[normal]who
[normal] has lived abroad for a substantial period may 
[normal]be unable to
[normal] establish 12
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]months residence in the UK as holders of British 
[normal]and EEA 
[normal]passports 
[normal]do
[normal] not have their passports stamped on entry to the UK
[normal] 
